ol.li:
Row reduction (specifically, subtracting the first row from the second) gives

							\amat{
							  1  -3  1  1;
	                  					 0  4  1  13
							}

        					shows, because the variable z does not have a pivot in the corresponding column, and hence is a free variable, that there are infinitely many solutions.

Row reduction (subtracting 3 times the first row from the second) gives

							\amat{
							 -1 -1 1;
                 						  0   0  -1
							}

					shows that there is no solution.

We begin by subtracting twice the first row from the fourth row and adding -\frac{3}{2} times the first row to the third row to obtain the matrix

							\amat{
							 2  0  1  1  5;
                   						0   1   0   -1  -1;
                  						 0  0   -\frac{5}{2}  -\frac{5}{2}   -\frac{15}{2};
                  						 0  1   0   -1  -1
							}

					Subtracting the second row from the fourth gives us the matrix

							\amat{
							 2  0  1 1 5;
                   						 0  1  0 -1  -1;
                  						 0  0 -\frac{5}{2}  -\frac{5}{2}   -\frac{15}{2} ;
                   						 0   0  0   0  0
							}

         					which shows that there are infinitely many solutions.

We first subtract the first row from the second and then add \frac{1}{2} times second row to the third row:


	    						\amat{
	    						 1  1  1 5; 
             						1 -1 0 0; 
                						0 1 2 7  
	    						}
	    						\quad\xrightarrow{R_2 = R_2 - R_1}\quad
	    						&\amat{
	    						1 1 1  5;  
            						0  -2  -1 -5;
                						0   1 2 7  
	    						}


	    						{}\quad\xrightarrow{R_3 = R_3 + \frac{3}{2} \times R_2}\quad
	    						&\amat{
	    						 1 1 1 5; 
             						0 -2 -1 -5; 
                						0 0 \frac{3}{2} \frac{9}{2}
	    						}


	    				This, followed by back-substitution gives x=1, y=1, and z=3.

Here we subtract \frac{1}{3} times the first row from the third and also subtract \frac{1}{3} of the first row from the second to obtain


	    						\amat{
	    						 3 0 1 7;  
                						1 -1 3 4;  
                						1 2 -5 -1;  
	    						}
	    						\quad\xrightarrow{R_3 = R_3-\frac{1}{3} \times R_1}\quad
	    						& \amat{
	    						3 0 1 7;
	    						1 -1 3 4;
	    						0 2 -\frac{16}{3} -\frac{10}{3}
	    						}


	    						{}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2 = R_2 - \frac{1}{3} \times R_1}\quad
	    						& \amat{
	    						3 0 1 7;
	    						0 -1 \frac{8}{3} \frac{5}{3};
	    						0 2 -\frac{16}{3} -\frac{10}{3}
	    						}


	    				Then, adding twice the second row to the third yields

	    						\amat{
	    						3 0  1 7; 
                   						0 -1 \frac{8}{3} \frac{5}{3};
                   						 0 0 0 0
	    						}

	    				and so one finds that the variable z is free (as there is not a pivot in the third column of the associated row-reduced matrix). Hence, there are infinitely many solutions.

Adding the first row to the second and third rows gives


	    						\amat{
	    						1 3 1 0; 
	    						-1 -1 0 2;
             						-1 1 2 8  
	    						}
	    						\quad\xrightarrow{R_2= R_2 + R_1}\quad
	    						& \amat{
	    						1 3 1 0;
	    						0 2 1 2;
	    						-1 1 2 8
	    						}


	    						\quad\xrightarrow{R_3= R_3 + R_1}\quad
	    						& \amat{
	    						1 3 1 0;
	    						0 2 1 2;
	    						0 4 3 8
	    						}


	    					and subtracting twice the second row from the third gives

	    						\amat{
	    						1 3 1 0;
	    						0 2 1 2;
	    						0 0 1 4
	    						}

	    					This yields the unique solution (x,y,z)=(-1,-1,4).

answer.p:
Subtract three times the first row from the second:

	    			\amat{
	    			 1 -1 1;
             			0 0 -3+k  
	    			}

	    			to conclude that this system has no solutions if k \neq 3and if k = 3 then it has infinitely many solutions. It never has a unique solution.
